## Business Logic

### 1. Summary of the Account Service

The Account Service is designed to manage user accounts through a RESTful API. It facilitates operations such as creating, retrieving, updating, and deleting accounts while ensuring data integrity and validation. The service utilizes a relational database for persistent data storage, while also integrating with a non-relational database for additional data management needs. The service includes exception handling for various scenarios, such as account not found or bad requests. Additionally, it employs messaging systems for asynchronous communication and event-driven architecture, enhancing the scalability and responsiveness of the application.

### 2. Service Overview Table

| **Base Path**           | `/accounts`                                                                                     |
|-------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Source Repository**   | [GitHub Repo Link](#) (Update with actual repository link)                                    |
| **Description**         | API for managing user accounts, including operations for creating, retrieving, updating, and deleting account information. |

### 3. Overall API Specification

| **Endpoint**             | **Method** | **Description**                              | **Request Body**                     | **Responses**                                                                 |
|--------------------------|------------|----------------------------------------------|--------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`              | GET        | Retrieve all accounts                        | None                                 | 200 OK - List of accounts (array)                                           |
| `/accounts`              | POST       | Create a new account                         | Account object                       | 201 Created - Account created successfully                                   |
| `/accounts/{id}`         | GET        | Retrieve account by ID                       | None                                 | 200 OK - Account details<br>404 Not Found - Account not found               |
| `/accounts/{id}`         | PUT        | Update an existing account                   | Account object                       | 200 OK - Account updated successfully<br>404 Not Found - Account not found   |
| `/accounts/{id}`         | DELETE     | Delete an account                            | None                                 | 204 No Content - Account deleted successfully<br>404 Not Found - Account not found |

### 4. Endpoints Overview

- **GET** `/accounts`: Retrieves a list of all accounts.
- **POST** `/accounts`: Creates a new account.
- **GET** `/accounts/{id}`: Retrieves a specific account by its ID.
- **PUT** `/accounts/{id}`: Updates an existing account by its ID.
- **DELETE** `/accounts/{id}`: Deletes an account by its ID.

This structured overview provides a comprehensive understanding of the Account Service, its functionalities, and its API specifications.

## Plant UML script

Here is the PlantUML sequence diagram script that captures the business logic, interactions, and processes as described:

```plantuml
@startuml
actor EndUser as User
participant "AccountController" as Controller
participant "AccountServiceImpl" as Service
participant "AccountFeignClient" as FeignClient
participant "PostgreSQL Database" as PostgreSQL
participant "MongoDB" as MongoDB
participant "Kafka Publisher" as Kafka
participant "RabbitMQ Publisher" as RabbitMQ
participant "Notification System" as Notification

== User Interaction ==
User -> Controller: HTTP GET /accounts
Controller -> Service: getAllAccounts()
Service -> PostgreSQL: fetchAllAccounts()
PostgreSQL --> Service: List of Accounts
Service --> Controller: 200 OK (List of Accounts)
Controller --> User: 200 OK (List of Accounts)

User -> Controller: HTTP POST /accounts\n(Account JSON)
Controller -> Service: createAccount(Account JSON)
Service -> PostgreSQL: checkAccountExists(accountId)
alt Account Exists
    Service --> Controller: BadRequestException
    Controller --> User: 400 Bad Request
else Account Not Exists
    Service -> FeignClient: validateAccount(accountId)
    alt Account Valid
        Service -> PostgreSQL: saveAccount(Account JSON)
        PostgreSQL --> Service: Account Created
        Service -> Kafka: publishAccountCreatedMessage(Account)
        Kafka --> Notification: Notify other services
        Service -> RabbitMQ: publishAccountCreationEvent(Account)
        RabbitMQ --> Notification: Notify other services
        Service --> Controller: 201 Created (Account)
        Controller --> User: 201 Created (Account)
    else Account Invalid
        Service --> Controller: ResourceNotFoundException
        Controller --> User: 404 Not Found
    end
end

User -> Controller: HTTP GET /accounts/{id}
Controller -> Service: getAccountById(accountId)
Service -> PostgreSQL: fetchAccountById(accountId)
alt Account Found
    PostgreSQL --> Service: Account
    Service --> Controller: 200 OK (Account)
    Controller --> User: 200 OK (Account)
else Account Not Found
    Service --> Controller: ResourceNotFoundException
    Controller --> User: 404 Not Found
end

User -> Controller: HTTP PUT /accounts/{id}\n(Account JSON)
Controller -> Service: updateAccount(accountId, Account JSON)
Service -> PostgreSQL: checkAccountExists(accountId)
alt Account Exists
    Service -> FeignClient: validateAccount(accountId)
    alt Account Valid
        Service -> PostgreSQL: updateAccount(accountId, Account JSON)
        PostgreSQL --> Service: Account Updated
        Service -> Kafka: publishAccountUpdatedMessage(Account)
        Kafka --> Notification: Notify other services
        Service -> RabbitMQ: publishAccountUpdateEvent(Account)
        RabbitMQ --> Notification: Notify other services
        Service --> Controller: 200 OK (Updated Account)
        Controller --> User: 200 OK (Updated Account)
    else Account Invalid
        Service --> Controller: ResourceNotFoundException
        Controller --> User: 404 Not Found
    end
else Account Not Exists
    Service --> Controller: ResourceNotFoundException
    Controller --> User: 404 Not Found
end

User -> Controller: HTTP DELETE /accounts/{id}
Controller -> Service: deleteAccount(accountId)
Service -> PostgreSQL: checkAccountExists(accountId)
alt Account Exists
    Service -> PostgreSQL: deleteAccount(accountId)
    PostgreSQL --> Service: Account Deleted
    Service -> Kafka: publishAccountDeletedMessage(accountId)
    Kafka --> Notification: Notify other services
    Service -> RabbitMQ: publishAccountDeletionEvent(accountId)
    RabbitMQ --> Notification: Notify other services
    Service --> Controller: 204 No Content
    Controller --> User: 204 No Content
else Account Not Exists
    Service --> Controller: ResourceNotFoundException
    Controller --> User: 404 Not Found
end
@enduml
```

### Explanation of the Diagram:
1. **Actors and Participants**: The diagram includes all key actors (End User, AccountController, AccountServiceImpl, AccountFeignClient, PostgreSQL, MongoDB, Kafka Publisher, RabbitMQ Publisher, and Notification System).
2. **Main Interactions**: It shows the sequence of interactions for each API endpoint (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) with detailed messages that represent the business logic and decision points.
3. **Decision Points**: The diagram highlights critical decision points, such as checking for existing accounts, validating accounts, and handling errors.
4. **Clear Messages**: Each interaction is described with clear messages to indicate the flow of data and actions taken.
5. **Endpoints**: All endpoints are included with their respective operations and responses.

# API Documentation

## Get All Accounts
Endpoint URL: `/accounts`  
HTTP Method: `GET`  
Authentication: None  
Authorization: None  
Description: Retrieves a list of all accounts in the system.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                      |
|----------------|--------|----------|----------------------------------|
| None           | N/A    | No       | No request parameters are needed.|

### Sample Request
```http
GET /accounts HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name | Type   | Description                       |
|------------|--------|-----------------------------------|
| accounts   | array  | List of account objects           |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john.doe@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "123456789",
      "accountType": "savings",
      "dob": "1990-01-01",
      "bankCode": "BANK001"
    },
    {
      "id": "2",
      "name": "Jane Smith",
      "email": "jane.smith@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "987654321",
      "accountType": "checking",
      "dob": "1985-05-15",
      "bankCode": "BANK002"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountService
- PostgreSQL Database

### Data Mapping
| Source Field | Target Field        | Transformation                |
|--------------|---------------------|-------------------------------|
| None         | AccountEntity       | Direct retrieval from DB      |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "No accounts found",
  "code": 404,
  "message": "No accounts exist in the system."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                     | Description                          | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                      |
|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|-----------------|--------|---------------------|----------------------------|
| ResourceNotFoundException | Thrown when no accounts are found    | N/A             | N/A    | Mandatory           | Indicates absence of data. |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                      | Description                               |
|-----------|------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
| 404       | No accounts found            | No accounts exist in the system.         |

## Create a New Account
Endpoint URL: `/accounts`  
HTTP Method: `POST`  
Authentication: None  
Authorization: None  
Description: Creates a new account in the system.  

### Request Parameters
| Parameter Name | Type   | Required | Description                      |
|----------------|--------|----------|----------------------------------|
| name           | string | Yes      | The name of the account holder.  |
| email          | string | Yes      | The email address of the account holder. |
| accountNumber  | string | Yes      | The account number.              |
| accountType    | string | Yes      | The type of account (e.g., savings, checking). |
| dob            | string | Yes      | The date of birth of the account holder (YYYY-MM-DD). |
| bankCode       | string | Yes      | The code of the associated bank. |

### Sample Request
```json
{
  "name": "Alice Johnson",
  "email": "alice.johnson@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1992-02-02",
  "bankCode": "BANK001"
}
```

### Response Parameters
| Field Name | Type   | Description                       |
|------------|--------|-----------------------------------|
| id         | string | The unique identifier for the account. |
| name       | string | The name of the account holder.   |
| email      | string | The email address of the account holder. |
| accountNumber | string | The account number.              |
| accountType | string | The type of account.             |
| dob        | string | The date of birth of the account holder. |
| bankCode   | string | The code of the associated bank. |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "id": "3",
  "name": "Alice Johnson",
  "email": "alice.johnson@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "savings",
  "dob": "1992-02-02",
  "bankCode": "BANK001"
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountService
- PostgreSQL Database
- Kafka Publisher
- RabbitMQ Publisher

### Data Mapping
| Source Field   | Target Field        | Transformation                |
|----------------|---------------------|-------------------------------|
| name           | AccountEntity.name  | Direct mapping                |
| email          | AccountEntity.email | Direct mapping                |
| accountNumber  | AccountEntity.accountNumber | Direct mapping        |
| accountType    | AccountEntity.accountType | Direct mapping          |
| dob            | AccountEntity.dob   | Direct mapping                |
| bankCode       | AccountEntity.bankCode | Direct mapping             |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": "Duplicate account ID",
  "code": 400,
  "message": "An account with this ID already exists."
}
```

### Root Exception Details
| Name                     | Description                          | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                      |
|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|-----------------|--------|---------------------|----------------------------|
| BadRequestException      | Thrown when there is a bad request   | N/A             | N/A    | Mandatory           | Indicates invalid request. |

### Error Codes
| HTTP Code | Message                      | Description                               |
|-----------|------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|
| 400       | Duplicate account ID         | An account with this ID already exists.   |
